By Adaeze Iroha Lagos, – A 40-year-old trader, Lawal Abideen, who allegedly assaulted two police officers who detained him for questioning, was on Monday brought before a Yaba Chief Magistrates’ Court in Lagos. Abideen, a resident of Shomolu area of Lagos, is facing a four-count charge bordering on assault and criminal damage to property. The Prosecutor, Sgt. Modupe Olaluwoye, told the court that the defendant committed the offences on May 11, at Pedro Police Station, Shomolu, in Yaba area of Lagos. According to her, the defendant was detained by two police officers; Sgt. Afolabi Abiodun and Sgt. Obadia Cholwe, in relation to an assault complaint filed against him. She told the court that Abideen had tried to escape from custody and had in the process assaulted the two officers. Olaluwoye further said that the defendant had bitten Abiodun on his left shoulder and had also torn his uniform and that of Cholwe. “My Lord, he also broke the station’s front window valued at N5,000 during his attempt to escape. It took three officers to restrain him,’’ she said. The offences contravened Sections 174 and 339 of the Criminal Laws of Lagos State, 2015 (Revised). The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that the offence of serious assault on a police officer stipulates three years imprisonment while criminal damage to property attracts seven years imprisonment. The Chief Magistrate, Mrs Oluwatoyin Oghere, granted the defendant bail in the sum of N200,000 with two sureties in like sum. Oghere said that the sureties must be gainfully employed and show evidence of three years’ tax payment to the Lagos State Government. The case was adjourned until June 26 for mention.